title: For Sale:  Serbu Super Shorty 870 AOW
postcontent:
The SUPER-SHORTY is considered an AOW (Any Other Weapon) and can be transferred with a $5 stamp! The gun holds two 2-3/4" or 3" shells in the magazine, plus one in the chamber. The 16.5" overall length, 6.5" barrel and spring-locked foregrip, which pivots out of the way when not in use, make for a very compact package. As far as I know, this is the shortest 12-gauge pump shotgun available. All parts for the SUPER-SHORTY are made in-house on their own CNC machinery using materials ideally suited to the task. All welds are done by the TIG process, and the manganese phosphate finish is MIL-spec. The SUPER-SHORTY is currently being used by various law enforcement agencies and military units worldwide. If you like the idea of concealed carry with a 12-gauge, or like a lot of "bang" in a small package, or just want the most compact breaching weapon available, then this is the gun for you. You won't find a better made AOW pump shotgun than the SUPER-SHORTY!

I am selling my Serbu because I really do not need an easily concealable 12 gauge nor do I need a special purpose breaching tool. This is classified as an NFA firearm but only requires a $5 tax stamp as opposed to the $200 for machine guns, short-barreled shotguns, and silencers, etc. This is the costlier model based off the Remington 870. This weapon has only been test fired by myself with Mark Serbu at his shop in Tampa. Otherwise, it's like new.

This sale will need to be handled by a CLASS III FFL holder in each state who is willing to complete the transfer. It will be the buyers responsibility for obtaining the approved ATF form 4 and working with the dealer. I will deliver the firearm to the Connecticut CLASS III FFL holder on the date of transfer at which time I will need to be paid in cash.

If you are unfamiliar with the process of purchasing an NFA firearm, please contact your local CLASS III FFL holder or the ATF. I will gladly answer any questions about my firearm but will not give any legal advice how to purchase this weapon with a CLEO sign-off like I did or through a corporation or trust. Thank you for your interest.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Springfield SAR-8 (HK-91, Helenic Arms, Greece) REDUCED
postcontent:
This is a Springfield SAR-8 sporter made in Greece. This is not to be confused with the newer (and vastly inferior) SAR-8 sold by Springfield with the cast aluminum receiver, this is all steel receiver, and not some parts kit build.
These are HK-91 clones made on HK tooling set-up by HK engineers, made by HK trained technicians at Hellenic Arms. These were imported by Springfield as SAR-3 for a while before being caught up in the early assault weapon ban. Springfield slapped a thumb hole stock on them, pinned and welded a non flash suppressor on them and overstamped the SAR-3 with an SAR-8. The quality on these is thought to be second only to HK since everything was set-up by HK.
 Included are 3x 20rd steel magazines, 5x 20 rd aluminum magazines, and the original 5 rd magazine. This rifle does have some small handling marks but is still in very good condition. title: For Sale:  XM21 Devine Texas Springfield Armory M1A
location: north carolina, North Carolina, United States
postcontent: For sale a Devine Texas M1A that is completely National Matched in the XM21 configuration. If you understand what Devine M1As are, I don't have to explain save for the fact that there were less than 2000 made. This one was made in 1971. I painstakingly converted the standard rifle into the XM21 over the period of several years. The gas system is unitized and the flash suppressor reamed by Ted Brown. Ted Brown also did a 4.5 lb trigger job. The stock is an original Sykes XM21 stock obtained from and bedded by Art Lupino. Op Rod Spring Guide is BPT. The scope is a genuine Redfield AR TEL scope which is serialized to match and marry it to the weapon as was done with XM21s. All the parts are original Springfield Armory marked. The Sparrow Hawk faux selector lock was installed by myself to complete package. The only thing NOT National Match is the barrel. This was not unheard of in the late 1960's when the XM21s were being built for Vietnam. Beside, if I changed the barrel, it would lose it's Devine Texas stampings and lose it's identity. Shoots between 1 and 1.25 MOA at 300 meters using M852 ammunition so it's a good shooter. More pictures can be provided on request.
